e of these shifts and contradictions, arguing that together they reveal a theopolitics that tries to balance the drive for U.S. dominance with the countervailing ideals and subjectivities of economic globalization. Examining the confluence of cultural formations, biblical interpretations, and (bio)political philosophies, The Babylon Complex shows how theopolitical arguments for war, sexual regulation, and political control both assuage and contribute to anxieties about waning national sovereignty. Theoretically sophisticated and engaging, this remarkable book complicates our understanding of how the Bible affects U.S political ideals and subjectivities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChristian sociologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aChurch and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSovereigntyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aWarxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aBabel. 4aBabylon. 4aTheopolitics. 4abiopolitics. 4adetranscendentalize. 4aglobalization. 4aqueer theory. 4asexuality. 4atorture. 4aviolence. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Exegesis & Hermeneutics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823257379zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823257379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823257379.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK